# Archibald Kennedy, 1st Marquess of Ailsa  

**{{Infobox nobility}}**  
'''Archibald Kennedy, 1st Marquess of Ailsa, KT, FRS''' (February 1770 – 8 September 1846) was a Scottish peer who sat in the [[House of Lords]] as a [[Scottish representative peer]] and later as a [[British peer]] after being raised to the peerage of the United Kingdom.  

He was styled **Lord Kennedy** between 1792 and 1794, then known as the [[Earl of Cassilis]] from 1794 to 1831, before being created [[Marquess of Ailsa]] in 1831.  

His full titles included **The Most Honourable** [[Lord Kennedy]] and later **Marquess of Ailsa**, a title that came with a hereditary seat in the [[House of Lords]].  

== Early life ==  

Archibald Kennedy was born in February 1770, the eldest son of [[Archibald Kennedy, 11th Earl of Cassilis]] and his second wife, Anne Watts.  His father had previously been married to and widowed by Katherine Schuyler, a daughter of [[Peter Schuyler (New Jersey soldier)]] and granddaughter of [[Arent Schuyler]].  After Katherine’s death in 1765, the entire estate passed to the younger Archibald, making him a substantial landowner in the [[Colony of New York]] before the American Revolution.  

His paternal grandparents were [[Archibald Kennedy]] (a direct descendant of the second son of the [[Gilbert Kennedy, 3rd Earl of Cassilis]]) and Maria (née Walter) Kennedy.  Through his mother, he was descended from [[John Watts (1715–1789)]] and Ann (née DeLancey) Watts, the latter being a granddaughter of [[Stephen Delancey]].  One of his uncles, [[John Watts (New York politician)]], served as a [[U.S. Representative]] and as the [[Speaker of the New York State Assembly]].  

Before inheriting his father’s titles, Kennedy held the [[courtesy title]] **Lord Kennedy**.  He was educated in the tradition of the Scottish aristocracy, preparing for a future in public service and the [[House of Lords]].  

== Career ==  

Kennedy succeeded to the earldom of Cassilis on the death of his father on 30 December 1794, at which point he automatically entered the [[House of Lords]] as a [[Scottish representative peer]].  He served in this capacity from 1796 until 1806, representing the interests of the Scottish peerage in the upper chamber.  

In 1806, he was created **Baron Ailsa** of Ailsa in the [[County of Ayr]], a new creation in the [[Peerage of the United Kingdom]] that granted him an automatic seat in the [[House of Lords]].  He was admitted as a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] on 18 February 1819, a testament to his interest in scientific inquiry and intellectual pursuits.  

In 1831, King [[George IV]] elevated him to the peerage of [[Marquess of Ailsa]], a title that combined the historic Scottish connection with a new rank in the British peerage.  As a [[Marquess of Ailsa]], he continued to sit in the [[House of Lords]] and took part in legislative debates, including his vote in favour of the [[Reform Bill]] of 1832, which reshaped the electoral map of Great Britain.  

He was also honoured with the [[Order of the Thistle]] (KT) in 1820, a distinction he had long coveted.  The honour was personally bestowed by the King and signalled his standing among the Scottish aristocracy.  

=== Gambling and sport ===  
Lord Ailsa possessed a well‑known taste for gambling.  He owned several racehorses, including **Clementina**, **Scaramouche**, **Pegasus**, **Chancellor**, and **Trimmer**, which competed in high‑profile meetings and won numerous cups in 1801 and 1802.  In 1801 he helped establish the [[Ayr Gold Cup]], an annual horse‑racing event that attracted Scottish‑trained horses over a two‑mile (3.2‑kilometre) course.  

=== Royal Society fellowship ===  
His election to the [[Royal Society]] reflected a broader interest in the scientific Enlightenment that was flourishing in Britain during the early nineteenth century.  Fellows of the Society were expected to contribute to the advancement of knowledge, and while his specific contributions are not extensively documented, his membership underscored the interdisciplinary nature of the British aristocracy at the time.  

== Personal life ==  

On 1 June 1793, Lord Ailsa married [[Margaret Erskine of Dun]] (1772–1848), the second daughter of Mary (née Baird) Erskine and John Erskine of [[House of Dun]] in [[Forfarshire]].  The marriage produced six children:  

* [[Archibald Kennedy, Earl of Cassilis]] (1794–1832), who predeceased his father; he married Eleanor Allardyce and had issue, including [[Archibald Kennedy, 2nd Marquess of Ailsa]].  
* Lady Anne Kennedy (1797–1877), who married [[Sir David Baird of Newbyth, 2nd Baronet]] and had issue.  
* Lady Mary Kennedy (1799–1886), who married [[Richard Oswald]], son of [[Richard Alexander Oswald]], MP for Ayr of [[Auchincruive]] Estate.  
* [[Lady Margaret Kennedy]] (1800–1889), who married [[Thomas Radclyffe-Livingstone-Eyre]].  
* The Hon. [[John Kennedy-Erskine]] of Dun (1802–1831), who assumed the additional name of Erskine after inheriting the [[Dun estate]] from his aunt in 1824; he married in 1827 [[Lady Augusta FitzClarence]], an illegitimate daughter of [[William IV of the United Kingdom]] and [[Dorothea Jordan]].  
* Lady Alicia Jane Kennedy (1805–1887), who married [[Jonathan Peel]], later [[Secretary of State for War]].  

The family maintained strong ties to both Scottish and English aristocratic circles, with several children marrying into other prominent families, thereby consolidating political and economic influence across the British Isles.  

Lord Ailsa died on 8 September 1846 and was succeeded in the marquessate by his grandson [[Archibald Kennedy, 2nd Marquess of Ailsa]].  

== Legacy ==  

Beyond his political and sporting pursuits, Lord Ailsa left a modest but lasting architectural imprint on [[Twickenham]], London.  He purchased a house that had formerly belonged to the playwright [[Richard Brinsley Sheridan]] and renamed it **St Margaret's**.  The name has persisted, with the surrounding area now commonly referred to as **St Margarets**.  Streets in the neighbourhood—namely **Ailsa Road** and **Ailsa Avenue**—continue to bear his name as a reminder of his connection to the district.  

His contributions to the Scottish peerage, his service in the [[House of Lords]], and his role in the early [[Reform Bill]] debates illustrate the intertwining of aristocratic privilege and emerging parliamentary democracy in the United Kingdom.  Historians also note his involvement in the cultural life of the period, including patronage of the arts and support for scientific societies such as the [[Royal Society]].  

